Millions of Americans are currently being affected by smoke from wildfires in Canada, highlighting the consequences of climate change. The United States has been assisting Canada in battling these wildfires since May, with over 600 firefighters and support personnel deployed. President Biden has offered additional help to Canada, particularly in Quebec where American communities are directly impacted. The National Interagency Fire Center has been directed to respond promptly to Canadian requests for more firefighters and fire suppression assets. Secretary of Transportation Buttigieg is monitoring air traffic implications due to the deteriorated air quality. The Environmental Protection Agency is continuously monitoring air quality and providing updates at AirNow.gov, while the Centers for Disease Control offer recommendations on protecting oneself from wildfire smoke at CDC.gov. It is important to stay safe and follow the guidance of local officials.